<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>London Councils Education Select Committee Evidence</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SCP0001</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by London Councils </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Current and future availability of school places </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All regions are experiencing a rise in demand for school places but this a pressure not spread evenly across the country. Over the 10 since Census 2001, London’s population grew by 900,000 (11.6 per cent). </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London Councils latest analysis has shown </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that between 2012/13 and 2016</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the shortage of school places is set to reach 118,000 - London represents a 42% share of the national need during this period. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">More than 34,356 school places have been created in the last two academic years to meet this school place pressure. A further 83,470 places, equivalent to 2783 classrooms, are needed to ensure London </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">meets the 118,000 place shortfall </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by 2016/17. This is split between primary and secondary as follows:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Primary school places - 69,455 </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Secondary school places  - 14,015</span></li></ul><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst this pressure is particularly acute within the primary phase, as children transfer to secondary school, the demand for places will also follow. In the next few years</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> boroughs face a tremendous challenge to meet the de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mand on secondary school places, with London representing a staggering 52% share of national demand – creating a dual challenge for London boroughs going forward. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Factors affecting the number of places available </span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For many local authorities, it is becoming increasingly challenging to create additional classrooms in existing schools. Where existing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">site and school </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">capacity has been maximised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> new schools will need to be built, which is increasingly difficult when both availability of appropriate land and funding are in short supply.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hile local authorities retain their statutory duty for school place planning, to provide a school place for every child resident in the borough, they no longer have the sole responsibility for commissioning new school places in a local are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a. Existing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, of which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> there are 369 in London, are responsible for their own expansion and should they opt to do so, bid directly to the Department for Education for funding. The Government also approves applications for new Free Schools without consultation with local authorities. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Within boroughs and across London, like all regions, engagement by academies to expand and liaison with Free School groups before they submit an application to government vary significantly. There is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">no systematic approach in place and many local authorities only find out about plans to expand or create new Free Schools once they have been approved by Government. This makes it difficult for local authorities to be able to include these new places in medium to long term place planning. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Current and future solution to address shortages</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> boroughs have used</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a range of creative solutions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to create both partial and permanent expansions to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">address</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the shortage of school places. This includes small scale projects such as purchasing tablets linking to a whiteboard to allow the use of ICT suites to be converted into classrooms through to full scale </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reconfiguration of sites</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to build new classrooms. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To avoid diminishing playground space, some boroughs have been able to build new classrooms and introduce roof top playgrounds – planning permission permitting. In other cases, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there have been first floor extensions to existing buildings. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With capacity now drying up, particularly for tight or limited sites, such expansions will not always be possible in the future resulting in a need for site acquisitions.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For secondary schools, where there will be demand imminently, it is a more complex business to expand due to the curriculum requiring additional science labs and more technology. Longer forward planning is needed and significant levels of investment. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> ability to respond to increased demand for places and role of government </span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London boroughs are exploiting every opportunity to provide every child with a high quality school place, but their ability is being </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">significantly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hindered by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">challenges beyond their control that put at risk providing the most basic of public services.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Insufficient funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London boroughs are facing a school places funding shortfall of £1 billion to ensure that every child has a school place up to 2016 – equivalent to £9,000 per new place. Money that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">boroughs have to find to subsidise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> inadequate government funding. In the current financial context where local government in London has experienced a 35% real terms decrease in funding, alongside huge and sustained demographic pressures, this ongoing funding shortfall is not sustainable and requires urgent Government attention.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At the same time, London local government also has responsibility to ensure that, in order to meet the needs of a growing population of all ages, London has the appropriate infrastructure in place and therefore, necessitates a need for long term and stable capital funding. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a considerable mismatch between government funding rates for school places and the actual outturn costs, a point highlighted by both the National Audit Office and Public Accounts Committee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Capital allocations are set using a government framework based on generic designs that were drafted without reference to a particular site and the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">refore, exclude essential work to create additional places. Meaning, funding is not sufficient to cover 100% the cost of school place creation. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Funding methodology</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – The Department has refined its methodology for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">national </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">capital allocations but further work is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> urgently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> needed. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">espite having 42% of the national shortfall of school places (inclusive of primary and secondary), London received 36% share of funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> under an improved system. In addition, money is still being allocated to areas of the country that do not have such an acute need as London. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of funding surety </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">his year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, for the first time,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Department made </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">basic need </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">funding available for two years up to 2015, allocations announcements were delayed by five months. Without funding guarantees, boroughs are legally unable to begin to commission place creation. London has been offered no funding surety for demand coming through in 2016/17 an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d beyond. This hinders planning for school places despite all evidence showing an urgent dual challenge of creating both primary and secondary schools in London.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Targeted Basic Need Programme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– Additional funding of £980m was made available for local authorities to bid for. Despite London’s need, boroughs had both bids and projects rejected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There also remains a total of £162million unallocated from programme funding.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>